{{for|similar terms|Athletics (disambiguation)|Athletic (disambiguation)}} {{DISPLAYTITLE:''The Athletic''}} {{Infobox website | name = The Athletic | logo = The Athletic.png | logo_size = 200px | logo_alt = | logo_caption = <!-- or: | logocaption = --> | screenshot = | collapsible = <!-- set as "on", "y", etc, otherwise omit/leave blank --> | collapsetext = <!-- collapsible area's heading (default "Screenshot"); omit/leave blank if collapsible not set --> | background = <!-- for collapsetext heading; default grey (gainsboro) --> | screenshot_size = | screenshot_alt = | caption = | url = <!-- {{URL|www.theathletic.com}} --> | commercial = Yes | type = [[Sports journalism]] | registration = Required | language = English, French (Montreal only) | num_users = | owner = <!-- or: | owners = --> | creators = Alex Mather and Adam Hansmann | editor = <!-- or: | editors = --> | launch_date = {{start date and age|2016|01}} | revenue = | alexa = <!-- {{increase}} {{steady}} {{decrease}} [http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/example.com ##] (US/Global MM/YYYY) --> | current_status = | footnotes = }}
'''''The Athletic''''' is a subscription-based sports website covering professional and college teams in Chicago, Toronto, and more than 30 other North American cities.<ref name="bloomberg2017">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-07-24/the-athletic-a-subscription-site-for-local-sports-news-raises-5-8-million|title=As ESPN Falters, Sports Startup Chases Fans Tired of ‘Old Fluff’|date=2017-07-24|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2017-08-17}}</ref> The site also covers national stories in football, basketball, baseball, hockey, and soccer through a mix of [[Long-form journalism|long-form]] journalism, original reporting, and [[podcast]]s. Their business model is predicated on dis-aggregating the sports section of local newspapers and reaching non-local fans that are not reached by a local newspaper.<ref name="Draper2017">{{cite news|last1=Draper|first1=Kevin|title=Why The Athletic Wants to Pillage Newspapers|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/23/sports/the-athletic-newspapers.html|accessdate=25 October 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=23 October 2017}}</ref>
{{TOC limit|2}}
== History == [[File:Profile TA gold.jpg|thumb|The Athletic app logo]] ''The Athletic'' was founded by Alex Mather and Adam Hansmann, former coworkers at subscription-based fitness company [[Strava]], with the mission of producing "smarter coverage for die-hard fans." The company was built as an alternative to the struggling ad-supported models.<ref name="bloomberg2017"/> ''The Athletic'' relies on subscription revenue, not advertising revenue, to support the business.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cjr.org/business_of_news/the-athletic-sports-news.php |title=Fast-growing startup aims to ‘replace the sports page’ |first=Tony |last=Biasotti |date=October 11, 2017 |work=Columbia Journalism Review}}</ref>
As part of [[Y Combinator (company)|Y Combinator]]'s Summer 2016 batch,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://blog.ycombinator.com/the-athletic/ |title=The Athletic gives diehard sports fans high-quality content without the ads |date=July 11, 2016 |publisher=Y Combinator}}</ref> the site originally launched in Chicago in January 2016,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://theathletic.com/480/2016/01/22/welcome-to-the-athletic/|title=Welcome Chicago, to The Athletic|date=January 22, 2016|work=The Athletic|access-date=2018-02-08}}</ref> with Jon Greenberg serving as the founding editor, along with Sahadev Sharma ([[Chicago Cubs|Cubs]]) and Scott Powers ([[Chicago Blackhawks|Blackhawks]]). Greenberg and Powers previously worked at ESPN Chicago, while Sharma left ''Baseball Prospectus''' Cubs vertical to join the website.
In October 2016, ''The Athletic'' expanded to a second city, Toronto, to focus on Maple Leafs, Raptors, and Blue Jays coverage. ''The Athletic'' hired James Mirtle as editor-in-chief for Toronto.<ref>{{cite twitter |user=mirtle |number=801452582602424321 |title=Excited to announce that I've been hired as editor-in-chief with @TheAthleticTO, a great new startup site in Toronto. |date=23 November 2016}}</ref> Mirtle spent over a decade as a sportswriter at ''The Globe and Mail'' before joining ''The Athletic''. A third city, Cleveland, launched in March 2017, with Jason Lloyd as editor-in-chief.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.crainscleveland.com/article/20170217/BLOGS06/170219821/the-athletic-soon-will-launch-a-cleveland-site-featuring-jason-lloyd |title=The Athletic soon will launch a Cleveland site featuring Jason Lloyd |date=February 17, 2017 |first=Kevin |last=Kleps |work=Crain's Cleveland Business}}</ref> ''The Athletic'' continued city expansion to Detroit in June 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.crainsdetroit.com/article/20170924/news/640081/the-athletic-paywall-sports-journalism-plants-its-flag-in-detroit |title=The Athletic: Paywall sports journalism plants its flag in Detroit |first=Bill |last=Shea |date=September 24, 2017 |work=Crain's Detroit Business}}</ref> In August, the site hired [[Ken Rosenthal]] as a senior baseball writer, shortly after Fox Sports eliminated its entire writing staff.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://theathletic.com/86701/2017/08/23/ken-rosenthal-why-im-joining-the-athletic/ |title=Ken Rosenthal: Why I’m joining The Athletic |first=Ken |last=Rosenthal |date=August 23, 2017 |work=The Athletic}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://awfulannouncing.com/fox/fox-sports-eliminates-digital-writing-staff-in-favor-of-promoting-their-debate-shows.html |title=Fox Sports eliminates digital writing staff in favor of promoting their debate shows |date=June 26, 2017 |work=Awful Announcing}}</ref>
The first major funding was provided by Courtside Ventures, which provided $2.3 million in seed funding.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.frontofficesports.org/sports-tech/2/22/the-athletic-paying-for-content-is-cool-again|title=High tech and high quality, The Athletic is bringing innovation to local sports coverage|work=Front Office Sports|access-date=2017-08-24|language=en-US}}</ref> In July 2017, the company raised another $5.8 million in funding and announced their expansion into the Philadelphia and San Francisco-area sports markets.<ref name="bloomberg2017"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bayareasportsguy.com/tim-kawakami-leaving-mercury-news-joining-the-athletic-san-francisco/|title=Interview: Tim Kawakami on leaving The Mercury News and joining The Athletic |work=Bay Area Sports Guy|access-date=2017-08-24|language=en-US}}</ref> ''The Athletic'' expanded into Minnesota and the rest of Canada in September 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://theathletic.com/90556/2017/09/05/introducing-the-athletic-canada-our-national-expansion-project/|title=Introducing The Athletic Canada, our national expansion...|work=The Athletic|access-date=2018-02-08}}</ref> In February 2018, ''The Athletic'' announced further expansion into three new cities—New York, Dallas, and Cincinnati—and launched baseball-only coverage in Houston, Los Angeles, San Diego, Arizona, and Kansas City.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://awfulannouncing.com/online-outlets/athletic-expanding-new-york-city-dallas-cincinnati.html|title=The Athletic is expanding to New York City, Dallas, and Cincinnati|date=2018-02-01|work=Awful Announcing|access-date=2018-02-08|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://awfulannouncing.com/mlb/athletic-launches-even-local-sites-seems-going-baseball.html |title=The Athletic launches even more local sites, seems to be going all-in on baseball |first=Alex |last=Putterman |date=2018-02-12|work=Awful Announcing}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/carolschram/2018/03/08/the-athletic-will-keep-growing-with-the-help-of-20-million-in-new-funding/#199b2fba5369 |title=The Athletic Will Keep Growing With The Help Of $20 Million In New Funding |first=Carol |last=Schram |date=2018-03-08 |work=Forbes.com}}</ref>
In March 2018, the company announced a $20 million third round of funding led by Evolution Media. Mather reported that this money would be invested into expanding coverage to new cities and increasing the number of writers from the then staff of 120.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-athletic-raises-20-million-to-fund-expansion-1520269215|title=The Athletic Raises $20 Million to Fund Expansion|last=Mullin|first=Benjamin|date=2018-03-05|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2018-03-20|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> That same month, the site announced full coverage in Denver and Boston starting in April.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://awfulannouncing.com/athletic/athletic-launches-coverage-denver-seattle-tampa-making-clear-wants-absolutely-every-market.html |title=The Athletic launches coverage in Denver, Seattle, and Tampa, making clear it wants to be everywhere |first=Alex |last=Putterman |date=2018-03-28 |work=Awful Announcing}}</ref> In Denver, ''The Athletic'' hired several reporters from ''[[The Denver Post]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.westword.com/news/denver-post-broncos-writers-leave-amid-layoffs-to-join-the-athletic-10129365 |title=Post Broncos Writer Joins Site She Saw as Trying to Destroy Newspapers |first=Michael |last=Roberts |date=2018-03-27 |work=Westword}}</ref> In Boston, the initial staff consisted of beat writers previously employed at the ''[[Boston Globe]]'', ''[[Boston Herald]]'' and the ''[[Springfield Republican]]'''s web portal [[MassLive]].<ref name=Finn20180329>Finn, Chad. "The Athletic is filling out its Boston roster", [https://www.boston.com/sports/media/2018/03/29/the-athletic-boston-roster Boston.com], 29 March 2018. Retrieved 4 April 2018.</ref> Adding to college football coverage, ''The Athletic'' added dedicated beat writers for major programs like [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]], [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]] and [[Tennessee Volunteers football|Tennessee]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://theathletic.com/319659/2018/04/18/the-all-new-all-american/|title=The All-New All-American|work=The Athletic|access-date=2018-04-24}}</ref> In May, the site announced coverage of both domestic and international soccer.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://theathletic.com/358023/2018/05/17/goooaaaalllll-announcing-the-athletics-soccer-coverage/ |title=Goooaaaalllll! Announcing The Athletic’s soccer coverage |first=George |last=Quraishi |date=May 17, 2018 |work=The Athletic}}</ref> In June 2018, ''The Athletic'' increased coverage in Los Angeles<ref>{{cite news |url=http://awfulannouncing.com/athletic/the-athletic-is-expanding-once-again-with-increased-coverage-in-los-angeles-dallas-buffalo.html |title=The Athletic is expanding once again, with increased coverage in Los Angeles, Dallas, Buffalo |date=June 18, 2018 |publisher=Awful Announcing}}</ref> and expanded into [[Buffalo, New York]] by hiring several reporters who had been bought out from ''[[The Buffalo News]]'' the same month.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailypublic.com/articles/06192018/news-etc-enter-athletic-buffalo|title=News, Etc.: Enter The Athletic Buffalo|first=Elmer|last=Ploetz|work=The Public|date=June 19, 2018|accessdate=June 22, 2018}}</ref>
